Here's a clean implementation using the MVVM Community Toolkit, which eliminates boilerplate:

```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.ComponentModel;
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Input;

namespace YourApp.ViewModels;

public partial class ProductDetailViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _name = string.Empty;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private decimal _price;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isAvailable;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isLoading;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task LoadAsync()
    {
        IsLoading = true;
        try
        {
            // Replace with your actual data service call
            await Task.Delay(500);

            Name = "Widget Pro";
            Price = 29.99m;
            IsAvailable = true;
        }
        finally
        {
            IsLoading = false;
        }
    }
}
```

**How it works:**

- `[ObservableProperty]` source-generates public properties (`Name`, `Price`, etc.) with `INotifyPropertyChanged` calls — no manual `OnPropertyChanged` needed.
- `[RelayCommand]` generates a `LoadCommand` (IAsyncRelayCommand) that also disables itself while running to prevent double-taps.
- The class must be `partial` so the source generator can emit the backing code.

**NuGet package needed:**

```
dotnet add package CommunityToolkit.Mvvm
```

**XAML binding example:**

```xml
<Label Text="{Binding Name}" />
<Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='{0:C}'}" />
<Switch IsToggled="{Binding IsAvailable}" />
<Button Text="Load" Command="{Binding LoadCommand}" />
<ActivityIndicator IsRunning="{Binding IsLoading}" IsVisible="{Binding IsLoading}" />
```
